      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Why? The Chelate Effect\n\nBoth ligands donate nitrogen lone pairs to Ni²⁺, but ethylenediamine (en) is a **bidentate chelate** — its two –NH₂ groups simultaneously coordinate to the same metal center, forming a stable five-membered ring. This confers a large **entropic advantage**: replacing two monodentate NH₃ molecules with one en molecule releases one extra water/solvent molecule and increases the disorder of the system (ΔS is more favorable). The thermodynamic data confirm this: for Ni²⁺–en, ΔH ≈ 0 kJ/mol while ΔS = +9.2 J/mol·K, meaning the binding is **entropy-driven** — a hallmark of the chelate effect. In contrast, Ni²⁺–NH₃ binding is **enthalpy-driven** (ΔH = −15.1 kJ/mol) but entropically unfavorable.\n\nThis ~4.6 log unit chelate advantage is consistent with the well-known rule of thumb that bidentate chelates are ~10³–10⁵ times more stable than analogous monodentate complexes.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46, vlm_173185 (NH₃) and vlm_122371 (en)*",
